<li id="cite_note-52"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-52">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Conquest, Robert (1997). "Victims of Stalinism: A Comment". <i>Europe-Asia Studies</i>. <b>49</b> (7): 1317–1319. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1080%2F09668139708412501">10.1080/09668139708412501</a>. <q>We are all inclined to accept the Zemskov totals (even if not as complete) with their 14 million intake to Gulag 'camps' alone, to which must be added 4–5&#160;million going to Gulag 'colonies', to say nothing of the 3.5&#160;million already in, or sent to, 'labour settlements'. However taken, these are surely 'high' figures.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Europe-Asia+Studies&amp;rft.atitle=Victims+of+Stalinism%3A+A+Comment&amp;rft.volume=49&amp;rft.issue=7&amp;rft.pages=1317-1319&amp;rft.date=1997&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1080%2F09668139708412501&amp;rft.au=Conquest%2C+Robert&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AStalinism" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
